# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: probabilistically-checkable-proofs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] In computational complexity theory, a **gap reduction** is a reduction to a particular type of decision problem, known as a *c-gap problem*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Such reductions provide information about the hardness of approximating solutions to optimization problems.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] In short, a gap problem refers to one wherein the objective is to distinguish between cases where the best solution is above one threshold from cases where the best solution is below another threshold, such that the two thresholds have a gap in between.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Gap reductions can be used to demonstrate inapproximability results, as if a problem may be approximated to a better factor than the size of gap, then the approximation algorithm can be used to solve the corresponding gap problem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Note that whenever OPT falls between the thresholds, there is no requirement on what the output should be.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] A valid algorithm for the c-gap problem may answer anything if OPT is in the middle of the gap.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] The value c does not need to be constant; it can depend on the size of the instance of P.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Note that c-approximating the solution to an instance of P is at least as hard as solving the c-gap version of P.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] One can define an **(*a*,*b*)-gap problem** similarly.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] The difference is that the thresholds do not depend on the input; instead, the lower threshold is a and the upper threshold is b.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] A gap-producing reduction is a reduction from an optimization problem to a c-gap problem, so that solving the c-gap problem quickly would enable solving the optimization problem quickly.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] The term gap-producing arises from the nature of the reduction: the optimal solution in the optimization problem maps to the opposite side of the gap from every other solution via reduction.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Thus, a gap is produced between the optimal solution and every other solution.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] A simple example of a gap-producing reduction is the nonmetric Traveling Salesman problem (i.e. where the graph's edge costs need not satisfy the conditions of a metric).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] We can reduce from the Hamiltonian path problem on a given graph G = (V, E) to this problem as follows: we construct a complete graph G' = (V, E'), for the traveling salesman problem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] For each edge e ∈ G', we let the cost of traversing it be 1 if e is in the original graph G and ∞ otherwise.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] A Hamiltonian path in the original graph G exists if and only if there exists a traveling salesman solution with weight (|V|-1).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] However, if no such Hamiltonian path exists, then the best traveling salesman tour must have weight at least |V|.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Thus, Hamiltonian Path reduces to |V|/(|V|-1)-gap nonmetric traveling salesman.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] A gap-preserving reduction is a reduction from a c-gap problem to a c'-gap problem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] More specifically, we are given an instance x of a problem A with |x| = n and want to reduce it to an instance x' of a problem B with |x'| = n'.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] If c' > c, then this is a *gap-amplifying reduction*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] This problem is a form of the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT), where each clause contains three distinct literals and we want to maximize the number of clauses satisfied.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Håstad showed that the (1/2+ε, 1-ε)-gap version of a similar problem, MAX E3-X(N)OR-SAT, is NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] The MAX E3-X(N)OR-SAT problem is a form of SAT where each clause is the XOR of three distinct literals, exactly one of which is negated.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] If a clause is not satisfied in the original instance of MAX E3-X(N)OR-SAT, then at most three of the four corresponding clauses in our MAX E3SAT instance can be satisfied.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Using a gap argument, it follows that a YES instance of the problem has at least a (1-ε) fraction of the clauses satisfied, while a NO instance of the problem has at most a (1/2+ε)(1) + (1/2-ε)(3/4) = (7/8 + ε/4)-fraction of the clauses satisfied.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Thus, it follows that (7/8 + ε, 1 - ε)-gap MAX E3SAT is NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Note that this bound is tight, as a random assignment of variables gives an expected 7/8 fraction of satisfied clauses.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] We define a "superedge" between Ai and Bj if at least one edge exists from Ai to Bj in G, and define the superedge to be covered if at least one edge from Ai to Bj is covered.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] In the *max-rep* version of the problem, we are allowed to choose one vertex from each Ai and each Bi, and we aim to maximize the number of covered superedges.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] In the *min-rep* version, we are required to cover every superedge in the graph, and want to minimize the number of vertices we choose.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/gap-reduction] Manurangsi and Moshkovitz show that the (O(n1/4), 1)-gap version of both problems is solvable in polynomial time.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] In computer science, **hardness of approximation** is a field that studies the algorithmic complexity of finding near-optimal solutions to optimization problems.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] Hardness of approximation complements the study of approximation algorithms by proving, for certain problems, a limit on the factors with which their solution can be efficiently approximated.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] Typically such limits show a factor of approximation beyond which a problem becomes NP-hard, implying that finding a polynomial time approximation for the problem is impossible unless NP=P.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] Some hardness of approximation results, however, are based on other hypotheses, a notable one among which is the unique games conjecture.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] Since the early 1970s it was known that many optimization problems could not be solved in polynomial time unless P = NP, but in many of these problems the optimal solution could be efficiently approximated to a certain degree.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] Gonzalez and Sartaj Sahni began the study of hardness of approximation, by showing that certain optimization problems were NP-hard even to approximate to within a given approximation ratio.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] That is, for these problems, there is a threshold such that any polynomial-time approximation with approximation ratio beyond this threshold could be used to solve NP-complete problems in polynomial time.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] In the early 1990s, with the development of PCP theory, it became clear that many more approximation problems were hard to approximate, and that (unless P = NP) many known approximation algorithms achieved the best possible approximation ratio.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] Hardness of approximation theory deals with studying the approximation threshold of such problems.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/hardness-of-approximation] For an example of an NP-hard optimization problem that is hard to approximate, see set cover and vertex cover.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In computational complexity theory, an **interactive proof system** is an abstract machine that models computation as the exchange of messages between two parties: a *prover* and a *verifier*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The parties interact by exchanging messages in order to ascertain whether a given string belongs to a language or not.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The prover is assumed to possess unlimited computational resources but cannot be trusted, while the verifier has bounded computation power but is assumed to be always honest.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Messages are sent between the verifier and prover until the verifier has an answer to the problem and has "convinced" itself that it is correct.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The specific nature of the system, and so the complexity class of languages it can recognize, depends on what sort of bounds are put on the verifier, as well as what abilities it is given—for example, most interactive proof systems depend critically on the verifier's ability to make random choices.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] It also depends on the nature of the messages exchanged—how many and what they can contain.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Interactive proof systems have been found to have some important implications for traditional complexity classes defined using only one machine.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The main complexity classes describing interactive proof systems are **AM** and **IP**.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Every interactive proof system defines a formal language of strings.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Often an interactive proof system is designed with the *intention* of being a system for a particular language L .
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] **Soundness** of the proof system refers to the property that no prover can make the verifier accept a string y when in fact $y\not \in L$ except with some small probability.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The upper bound of this probability is referred to as the **soundness error** of a proof system.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] As long as the soundness error is bounded by a polynomial fraction of the potential running time of the verifier (i.e. $\epsilon \leq 1/\mathrm {poly} (|y|)$ ), it is always possible to amplify soundness until the soundness error becomes a negligible function of the running time of the verifier.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This is achieved by repeating the proof and accepting only if all proofs verify.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] After $\ell$ repetitions, a soundness error $\epsilon$ will be reduced to $\epsilon ^{\ell }$ .
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The complexity class NP may be viewed as a very simple proof system.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In this system, the verifier is a deterministic, polynomial-time machine (a P machine).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In the case where a valid proof certificate exists, the prover is always able to make the verifier accept by giving it that certificate.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In the case where there is no valid proof certificate, however, the input is not in the language, and no prover, however malicious it is, can convince the verifier otherwise, because any proof certificate will be rejected.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Although NP may be viewed as using interaction, it wasn't until 1985 that the concept of computation through interaction was conceived (in the context of complexity theory) by two independent groups of researchers.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] One approach, by László Babai, who published "Trading group theory for randomness", defined the *Arthur–Merlin* (**AM**) class hierarchy.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In this presentation, Arthur (the verifier) is a probabilistic, polynomial-time machine, while Merlin (the prover) has unbounded resources.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The class **MA** in particular is a simple generalization of the NP interaction above in which the verifier is probabilistic instead of deterministic.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This machine is potentially more powerful than an ordinary NP interaction protocol, but the certificates are no less practical to verify, since **BPP** algorithms are considered as abstracting practical computation (see BPP).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In a *public coin* protocol, the random choices made by the verifier are made public.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] They remain private in a private coin protocol.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In the same conference where Babai defined his proof system for **MA**, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali and Charles Rackoff published a paper defining the interactive proof system **IP**[*f*(*n*)].
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This has the same machines as the **MA** protocol, except that *f*(*n*) *rounds* are allowed for an input of size *n*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In each round, the verifier performs computation and passes a message to the prover, and the prover performs computation and passes information back to the verifier.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] At the end the verifier must make its decision.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] For example, in an **IP**[3] protocol, the sequence would be VPVPVPV, where V is a verifier turn and P is a prover turn.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In Arthur–Merlin protocols, Babai defined a similar class **AM**[*f*(*n*)], which allowed *f*(*n*) rounds, but he put one extra condition on the machine: the verifier must show the prover all the random bits it uses in its computation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The result is that the verifier cannot "hide" anything from the prover, because the prover is powerful enough to simulate everything the verifier does if it knows what random bits it used.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This is called a *public coin* protocol, because the random bits ("coin flips") are visible to both machines.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The **IP** approach is called a *private coin* protocol by contrast.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The essential problem with public coins is that if the prover wishes to maliciously convince the verifier to accept a string that is not in the language, it seems like the verifier might be able to thwart its plans if it can hide its internal state from it.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This was a primary motivation in defining the **IP** proof systems.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In 1986, Goldwasser and Sipser showed, perhaps surprisingly, that the verifier's ability to hide coin flips from the prover does it little good after all, in that an Arthur–Merlin public coin protocol with only two more rounds can recognize all the same languages.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The result is that public-coin and private-coin protocols are roughly equivalent.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] To demonstrate the power of these classes, consider the graph isomorphism problem, the problem of determining whether it is possible to permute the vertices of one graph so that it is identical to another graph.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This problem is in **NP**, since the proof certificate is the permutation that makes the graphs equal.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] It turns out that the complement of the graph isomorphism problem, a co-**NP** problem not known to be in **NP**, has an **AM** algorithm and the best way to see it is via a private coins algorithm.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Private coins may not be helpful, but more rounds of interaction are helpful.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] If we allow the probabilistic verifier machine and the all-powerful prover to interact for a polynomial number of rounds, we get the class of problems called **IP**.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In 1992, Adi Shamir revealed in one of the central results of complexity theory that **IP** equals **PSPACE**, the class of problems solvable by an ordinary deterministic Turing machine in polynomial space.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] If we allow the elements of the system to use quantum computation, the system is called a **quantum interactive proof system**, and the corresponding complexity class is called **QIP**.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] A series of results culminated in a 2010 breakthrough that **QIP** = **PSPACE**.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Not only can interactive proof systems solve problems not believed to be in **NP**, but under assumptions about the existence of one-way functions, a prover can convince the verifier of the solution without ever giving the verifier information about the solution.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This is important when the verifier cannot be trusted with the full solution.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] At first it seems impossible that the verifier could be convinced that there is a solution when the verifier has not seen a certificate, but such proofs, known as zero-knowledge proofs are in fact believed to exist for all problems in **NP** and are valuable in cryptography.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Zero-knowledge proofs were first mentioned in the original 1985 paper on **IP** by Goldwasser, Micali and Rackoff for specific number-theoretic languages.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The extent of their power was however shown by Oded Goldreich, Silvio Micali and Avi Wigderson for all of **NP**, and this was first extended by Russell Impagliazzo and Moti Yung to all of **IP**.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] One goal of **IP'**s designers was to create the most powerful possible interactive proof system, and at first it seems like it cannot be made more powerful without making the verifier more powerful and so impractical.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Goldwasser et al. overcame this in their 1988 "Multi prover interactive proofs: How to remove intractability assumptions", which defines a variant of **IP** called **MIP** in which there are *two* independent provers.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The two provers cannot communicate once the verifier has begun sending messages to them.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Just as it's easier to tell if a criminal is lying if he and his partner are interrogated in separate rooms, it's considerably easier to detect a malicious prover trying to trick the verifier into accepting a string not in the language if there is another prover it can double-check with.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In fact, this is so helpful that Babai, Fortnow, and Lund were able to show that **MIP** = **NEXPTIME**, the class of all problems solvable by a nondeterministic machine in *exponential time*, a very large class.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] NEXPTIME contains PSPACE, and is believed to strictly contain PSPACE.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Adding a constant number of additional provers beyond two does not enable recognition of any more languages.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This result paved the way for the celebrated PCP theorem, which can be considered to be a "scaled-down" version of this theorem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] It is known that for any constant *k*, an MIP system with *k* provers and polynomially many rounds can be turned into an equivalent system with only 2 provers, and a constant number of rounds.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] While the designers of **IP** considered generalizations of Babai's interactive proof systems, others considered restrictions.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] A very useful interactive proof system is **PCP**(*f*(*n*), *g*(*n*)), which is a restriction of **MA** where Arthur can only use *f*(*n*) random bits and can only examine *g*(*n*) bits of the proof certificate sent by Merlin (essentially using random access).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Furthermore, the PCP theorem asserts that the number of proof accesses can be brought all the way down to a constant.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] They used this valuable characterization of **NP** to prove that approximation algorithms do not exist for the optimization versions of certain NP-complete problems unless P = NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Such problems are now studied in the field known as hardness of approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The PCP theorem is the cornerstone of the theory of computational hardness of approximation, which investigates the inherent difficulty in designing efficient approximation algorithms for various optimization problems.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] It has been described by Ingo Wegener as "the most important result in complexity theory since Cook's theorem" and by Oded Goldreich as "a culmination of a sequence of impressive works […] rich in innovative ideas".
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The variable n is the length in bits of the description of a problem instance.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] Note further that the verification algorithm is *non-adaptive*: the choice of bits of the proof to check depend only on the random bits and the description of the problem instance, not the actual bits of the proof.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] An alternative formulation of the PCP theorem states that the maximum fraction of satisfiable constraints of a certain constraint satisfaction problem is NP-hard to approximate within some constant factor.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] where $\Phi$ is a constraint satisfaction problem (CSP) over a Boolean alphabet with at most q variables per constraint.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The connection to the class ${\mathsf {PCP}}$ mentioned above can be seen by noticing that checking a constant number of bits q in a proof can be seen as evaluating a constraint in q Boolean variables on those bits of the proof.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] Since the verification algorithm uses $O(\log n)$ bits of randomness, it can be represented as a CSP as described above with $\operatorname {poly} (n)$ constraints.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] Therefore, an algorithm for the promise problem would be able to solve the underlying NP problem, and hence the promise problem must be NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] This can be done by reducing the problem of approximating a solution to such problems to a promise problem of the above form.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] These results are sometimes also called PCP theorems because they can be viewed as probabilistically checkable proofs for NP with some additional structure.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] A proof of a weaker result, ⁠ ${\mathsf {NP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {PCP}}[n^{3},1]$ ⁠ is given in one of the lectures of Dexter Kozen.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The PCP theorem is the culmination of a long line of work on interactive proofs and probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The first theorem relating standard proofs and probabilistically checkable proofs is the statement that ${\mathsf {NEXP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {PCP}}[\operatorname {poly} (n),\operatorname {poly} (n)]$ , proved by Babai, Fortnow & Lund (1990).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The notation ${\mathsf {PCP}}_{c(n),s(n)}[r(n),q(n)]$ is explained at probabilistically checkable proof.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The notation is that of a function that returns a certain complexity class.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The name of this theorem (the "PCP theorem") probably comes either from **"PCP"** meaning "probabilistically checkable proof", or from the notation mentioned above (or both).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] Subsequently, the methods used in this work were extended by Babai, Lance Fortnow, Levin, and Szegedy in 1991 (Babai et al.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] 1991), Feige, Goldwasser, Lund, Safra, and Szegedy (1991), and Arora and Safra in 1992 (Arora & Safra 1992) to yield a proof of the PCP theorem by Arora, Lund, Motwani, Sudan, and Szegedy in 1998 (Arora et al.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The 2001 Gödel Prize was awarded to Sanjeev Arora, Uriel Feige, Shafi Goldwasser, Carsten Lund, László Lovász, Rajeev Motwani, Shmuel Safra, Madhu Sudan, and Mario Szegedy for work on the PCP theorem and its connection to hardness of approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] In 2005 Irit Dinur discovered a significantly simpler proof of the PCP theorem, using expander graphs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] She received the 2019 Gödel Prize for this.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] A version of the PCP theorem for quantum nonlocal games would state that it is computationally hard to approximate the quantum value of a quantum nonlocal game.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] In 2012, Thomas Vidick and Tsuyoshi Ito published a result that showed a "strong limitation on the ability of entangled provers to collude in a multiplayer game".
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] This could be a step toward proving the quantum analogue of the PCP theorem, since when the result was reported in the media, professor Dorit Aharonov called it "the quantum analogue of an earlier paper on multiprover interactive proofs" that "basically led to the PCP theorem".
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] In 2018, Thomas Vidick and Anand Natarajan proved a games variant of quantum PCP theorem under randomized reduction.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] It states that ${\mathsf {QMA}}\subseteq {\mathsf {MIP}}^{*}[\log n,1,{\tfrac {1}{2}}]$ , where ${\mathsf {MIP}}^{*}[f(n),c,s]$ is a complexity class of multi-prover quantum interactive proofs systems with $f(n)$ -bit classical communications, and the completeness is c and the soundness is s .
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] A version of the PCP theorem for quantum local Hamiltonians would state that it is computationally hard to approximate the ground energy of a quantum local Hamiltonian.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The work of Natarajan and Vidick also showed that a quantum Hamiltonian version of the PCP theorem, namely the existence of local Hamiltonian problem with constant promise gap $c-s$ which are QMA-hard, implies a quantum nonlocal games version of the PCP theorem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The NLTS conjecture was an unresolved obstacle and precursor to a quantum Hamiltonian analog of the PCP theorem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] The conjecture was proven in 2022 by Anurag Anshu, Nikolas Breuckmann, and Chinmay Nirkhe using a construction of a Hamiltonian based on quantum CSS codes.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/pcp-theorem] However, the ground states of such Hamiltonians are given explicitly by the code states of the corresponding CSS code, and thus are not computationally hard enough for a general proof of a quantum PCP theorem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] In computational complexity theory, a **probabilistically checkable proof** (**PCP**) is a type of proof that can be checked by a randomized algorithm using a bounded amount of randomness and reading a bounded number of bits of the proof.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The algorithm is then required to accept correct proofs and reject incorrect proofs with very high probability.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] A standard proof (or certificate), as used in the verifier-based definition of the complexity class NP, also satisfies these requirements, since the checking procedure deterministically reads the whole proof, always accepts correct proofs and rejects incorrect proofs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] However, what makes them interesting is the existence of probabilistically checkable proofs that can be checked by reading only a few bits of the proof using randomness in an essential way.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] Probabilistically checkable proofs give rise to many complexity classes depending on the number of queries required and the amount of randomness used.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The class PCP[*r*(*n*), *q*(*n*)] refers to the set of decision problems that have probabilistically checkable proofs that can be verified in polynomial time using at most *r*(*n*) random bits and by reading at most *q*(*n*) bits of the proof.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] Unless specified otherwise, correct proofs should always be accepted, and incorrect proofs should be rejected with probability greater than 1/2.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The PCP theorem, a major result in computational complexity theory, states that PCP[*O*(log *n*), *O*(1)] = NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] Given a decision problem *L* (a language over an alphabet Σ), a **probabilistically checkable proof system** for *L* with completeness *c*(*n*) and soundness *s*(*n*), where 0 ≤ *s*(*n*) ≤ *c*(*n*) ≤ 1, consists of a prover and a verifier.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] Given a claimed solution *x* of length *n*, which might be false, the prover produces a proof *π* which states *x* solves L (*x* ∈ *L*, the proof is a string in Σ∗).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] And the verifier is a randomized oracle Turing Machine *V* (the *verifier*) that checks the proof *π* for the statement that *x* solves L (or *x* ∈ *L*) and decides whether to accept the statement.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] In the above definition, the length of proof is not mentioned since usually it includes the alphabet set and all the witnesses.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] For the prover, we do not care how it arrives at the solution to the problem; we care only about the proof it gives of the solution's membership in the language.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The verifier is said to be *non-adaptive* if it makes all its queries before it receives any of the answers to previous queries.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The theory of probabilistically checkable proofs studies the power of probabilistically checkable proof systems under various restrictions of the parameters (completeness, soundness, randomness complexity, query complexity, and alphabet size).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] It has applications to computational complexity (in particular hardness of approximation) and cryptography.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The definition of a probabilistically checkable proof was explicitly introduced by Arora and Safra in 1992, although their properties were studied earlier.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] In 1990 Babai, Fortnow, and Lund proved that **PCP**[poly(*n*), poly(*n*)] = **NEXP**, providing the first nontrivial equivalence between standard proofs (**NEXP**) and probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The PCP theorem proved in 1992 states that PCP[*O*(log *n*),*O*(1)] = NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] The theory of hardness of approximation requires a detailed understanding of the role of completeness, soundness, alphabet size, and query complexity in probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] From computational complexity point of view, for extreme settings of the parameters, the definition of probabilistically checkable proofs is easily seen to be equivalent to standard complexity classes.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] On the other hand, if NP ⊆ PCP [*o*(log *n*),*o*(log *n*)] then P = NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] A Linear PCP is a PCP in which the proof is a vector of elements of a finite field $\pi \in \mathbb {F} ^{n}$ , and such that the PCP oracle is only allowed to do linear operations on the proof.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] Namely, the response from the oracle to a verifier query $q\in \mathbb {F} ^{n}$ is a linear function $f(q,\pi )$ .
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/probabilistically-checkable-proof] Linear PCPs have important applications in proof systems that can be compiled into SNARKs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In computational complexity theory, the **unique games conjecture** (often referred to as **UGC**) is a conjecture made by Subhash Khot in 2002.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The conjecture postulates that the problem of determining the approximate *value* of a certain type of game, known as a *unique game*, has NP-hard computational complexity.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] It has broad applications in the theory of hardness of approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] If the unique games conjecture is true and P ≠ NP, then for many important problems it is not only impossible to get an exact solution in polynomial time (as postulated by the P versus NP problem), but also impossible to get a good polynomial-time approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The problems for which such an inapproximability result would hold include constraint satisfaction problems, which crop up in a wide variety of disciplines.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] According to Ryan O'Donnell as quoted by the Simons Foundation, academics are roughly evenly divided on whether the conjecture is true or false.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The unique games conjecture can be stated in a number of equivalent ways.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The following formulation of the unique games conjecture is often used in hardness of approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The conjecture postulates the NP-hardness of the following promise problem known as *label cover with unique constraints*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] For each edge, the colors on the two vertices are restricted to some particular ordered pairs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] *Unique* constraints means that for each edge none of the ordered pairs have the same color for the same node.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] This means that an instance of label cover with unique constraints over an alphabet of size k can be represented as a directed graph together with a collection of permutations $\pi _{e}:[k]\to [k]$ , one for each edge e of the graph.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] An assignment to a label cover instance gives to each vertex of G a value in the set $[k]=\{1,2,\ldots ,k\}$ , often called “colours”.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Such instances are strongly constrained in the sense that the colour of a vertex uniquely defines the colours of its neighbours, and hence for its entire connected component.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Thus, if the input instance admits a valid assignment, then such an assignment can be found efficiently by iterating over all colours of a single node.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In particular, the problem of deciding if a given instance admits a satisfying assignment can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The *value* of a unique label cover instance is the fraction of constraints that can be satisfied by any assignment.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] For satisfiable instances, this value is 1 and is easy to find.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] On the other hand, it seems to be very difficult to determine the value of an unsatisfiable game, even approximately.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The unique games conjecture formalises this difficulty.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] where G is an instance of the label cover problem with unique constraints.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The unique games conjecture states that for every sufficiently small pair of constants $\varepsilon ,\delta >0$ , there exists a constant k such that the $(1-\delta ,\varepsilon )$ -gap label-cover problem with unique constraints over alphabet of size k is NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] It is not immediately obvious that the inapproximability of Max2Lin(k) is equivalent to the UGC, but this is in fact the case, by a reduction.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Namely, the UGC is equivalent to: for every sufficiently small pair of constants *ε*, *δ* > 0, there exists a constant *k* such that the (1 − *δ*, *ε*)-gap Max2Lin(k) problem is NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] It has been argued that the UGC is essentially a question of computational topology, involving local-global principles (the latter are also evident in the proof of the 2-2 Games Conjecture, see below).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Linial observed that unique label cover is an instance of the Maximum Section of a Covering Graph problem (covering graphs is the terminology from topology; in the context of unique games these are often referred to as graph lifts).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] To date, all known problems whose inapproximability is equivalent to the UGC are instances of this problem, including Unique Label Cover and Max2Lin(k).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] When the latter two problems are viewed as instances of Max Section of a Covering Graph, the reduction between them preserves the structure of the graph covering spaces, so not only the problems, but the reduction between them has a natural topological interpretation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Grochow and Tucker-Foltz exhibited a third computational topology problem whose inapproximability is equivalent to the UGC: 1-Cohomology Localization on Triangulations of 2-Manifolds.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A **unique game** is a special case of a *two-prover one-round (2P1R) game*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A two-prover one-round game has two players (also known as provers) and a referee.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The referee sends each player a question drawn from a known probability distribution, and the players each have to send an answer.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The answers come from a set of fixed size.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The game is specified by a predicate that depends on the questions sent to the players and the answers provided by them.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The players may decide on a strategy beforehand, although they cannot communicate with each other during the game.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The players win if the predicate is satisfied by their questions and their answers.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A two-prover one-round game is called a *unique game* if for every question and every answer by the first player, there is exactly one answer by the second player that results in a win for the players, and vice versa.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The *value* of a game is the maximum winning probability for the players over all strategies.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] where *G* is a unique game whose answers come from a set of size *k*.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Alternatively, the unique games conjecture postulates the existence of a certain type of probabilistically checkable proof for problems in NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The unique games conjecture was introduced by Subhash Khot in 2002 in order to make progress on certain questions in the theory of hardness of approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The truth of the unique games conjecture would imply the optimality of many known approximation algorithms (assuming P ≠ NP).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] For example, the approximation ratio achieved by the algorithm of Goemans and Williamson for approximating the maximum cut in a graph is optimal to within any additive constant assuming the unique games conjecture and P ≠ NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A list of results that the unique games conjecture is known to imply is shown in the adjacent table together with the corresponding best results for the weaker assumption P ≠ NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A constant of $c+\varepsilon$ or $c-\varepsilon$ means that the result holds for every *constant* (with respect to the problem size) strictly greater than or less than c , respectively.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Currently, there is no consensus regarding the truth of the unique games conjecture.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Certain stronger forms of the conjecture have been disproved.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A different form of the conjecture postulates that distinguishing the case when the value of a unique game is at least $1-\delta$ from the case when the value is at most $\varepsilon$ is impossible for polynomial-time algorithms (but perhaps not NP-hard).
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] This form of the conjecture would still be useful for applications in hardness of approximation.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The constant $\delta >0$ in the above formulations of the conjecture is necessary unless P = NP.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] If the uniqueness requirement is removed the corresponding statement is known to be true by the parallel repetition theorem, even when $\delta =0$ .
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] Marek Karpinski and Warren Schudy have constructed linear time approximation schemes for dense instances of unique games problem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In 2008, Prasad Raghavendra has shown that if the unique games conjecture is true, then for every constraint satisfaction problem the best approximation ratio is given by a certain simple semidefinite programming instance, which is in particular polynomial.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In 2010, Prasad Raghavendra and David Steurer defined the *gap-small-set expansion* problem, and conjectured that it is NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The resulting small set expansion hypothesis implies the unique games conjecture.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] It has also been used to prove strong hardness of approximation results for finding complete bipartite subgraphs.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In 2010, Sanjeev Arora, Boaz Barak and David Steurer found a subexponential time approximation algorithm for the unique games problem.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] A key ingredient in their result was the spectral algorithm of Alexandra Kolla (see also the earlier manuscript of A.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] The latter also re-proved that unique games on expander graphs could be solved in polynomial time, and was one of (if not the) first graph algorithms to take advantage of the full spectrum of a graph rather than just its first two eigenvalues.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In 2012, it was shown that distinguishing instances with value at most ${\tfrac {3}{8}}+\delta$ from instances with value at least ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ is NP-hard.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In 2018, after a series of papers, a weaker version of the conjecture, called the 2-2 games conjecture, was proven.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] In a certain sense, this proves "a half" of the original conjecture.
[src:probabilistically-checkable-proofs/unique-games-conjecture] This also improves the best known gap for unique label cover: it is NP-hard to distinguish instances with value at most $\delta$ from instances with value at least ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
